    "title": "Islam & the Rise of Western Humanism",
    "slug": "islam-the-rise-of-western-humanism",
    "bodyHtml": "<ul><li>Few ideals are valued higher in Western Europe and North America than humanism <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Western humanism is also indebted to humanistic convictions and philosophies that arose in the Muslim world centuries before <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>There is also a strong connection between the rise of Western humanism and the broad Islamic intellectual tradition <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>A distinctive brand of humanism was cultivated in the Muslim world among litterateurs and chancellery scribes <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Like classical European humanism, the humanism that grew out of Muslim literary circles and the chancellery placed great emphasis upon the mastery of classical languages <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>“I have read, reverend Fathers, in the works of the Arabs, that when Abdala the Saracen was asked what he regarded as most to be wondered at on the world’s stage, so to speak, he answered that there was nothing to be seen more wonderful than man” <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Ibn Qutayba wrote a work on the dignity of man six hundred years before Pico <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Pico was, without question, one of the most important figures of the early Western Renaissance <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>His primary teacher was steeped in the Aristotelian philosophy of Ibn Rushd <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Islamic Universal Humanism in the classical Islamic tradition is reflected, for example, in the saying that the perfect Muslim believer should be “Arab in faith; Persian in the derivation of meanings; Babylonian in education; Hebrew in astuteness; a disciple of Christ in conduct; a Syrian monk in piety; a Greek in the individual sciences; an Indian in the interpretation of the secrets of reality; and a Sufi in one’s entire spiritual life” <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>The beginning of self-control is a victory of transcendence <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>The man of self-control is he who can consistently perform the feat of abstraction <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>The traditional notion of the human being as a microcosm and the objective world as a macrocosm is a radically different contrary paradigm <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>The human being participates directly in the world he or she perceives <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>This may also be called the paradigm of transcendent humanism <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Transcendental humanism aspires to human perfection as a reality—not just an ideal <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Natural values have no effective value except when they are integrated into supernatural or metaphysical virtues <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Finally, there is the third and highest stage of true Freedom as attained by the Minority of the Minority <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>This is what we may call the epitome of transcendental humanism, which is the centerpiece of Islamic civilization <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>The believer whom God honors with such true Freedom is referred to as “the one emancipated by the All-Compassionate” (‘atīq al-Raḥmān) <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Transcendent Humanism = the Ultimate of Human Perfection <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>The goal of religion is the achievement of human perfection in 3 modalities: 1) works, 2) states, and 3) knowledge <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Sufi knowledge meant to be able to discern and to put all things in their proper places <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>To distinguish what is real from what is illusory and to devote your life to what is real <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>There is no god but God. There is no man without God <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Government chanceries were the training schools for secretaries of all levels who served in government <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>They were the nurseries of the secretaries and the backbone of Islamic humanism <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>“They are not boring. They can be trusted in our absence, as in our presence… Were you to say they are dead, you would not be guilty of lying; were you to say they are living, you would not be proven false” <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li></ul>"
