    "index": 59,
    "title": "Islam & the Western Enlightenment",
    "slug": "islam-the-western-enlightenment",
    "bodyHtml": "<ul><li>Even the Enlightenment of twelfth/eighteenth century Western Europe was deeply influenced by the Islamic intellectual tradition <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>The origins of the Enlightenment are deeply indebted to “a pioneering community of Christian scholars” who journeyed to the Muslim world <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>These scholars spearheaded a new approach to Islam and Islamic civilization <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>These scholarly efforts arose—not from a secular agenda—but from the fidelity and hard work of committed Christians <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Even during the sixteenth and seventeenth century, there were remarkable parallels in literature, music, and the arts and sciences between the centers of Renaissance creativity in Italy and the wealthy and worldly courts of the gunpowder empires of the Muslim Ottomans, Safavids, and Mughals <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>The work Ḥayy ibn Yaqẓān became a major work in Arabic literature and influenced the development of European literature as well <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>It tells the imaginary story of a child, Ḥayy ibn Yaqẓān, who finds himself alone on a desert island and is raised by a gazelle <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Ḥayy discovers ultimate truths through an autodidactic process of systematic inquiry and reason <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>The work influenced the development of both Muslim and Western philosophical thought <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>The first Latin translation of Ḥayy ibn Yaqẓān was published in 1082/1671 by Edward Pococke the Younger <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>It may have influenced the deserted island narrative of Daniel Defoe in his conception of Robinson Crusoe <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Ḥayy ibn Yaqẓān may also have influenced John Locke’s notion of the human mind as a “blank slate” <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>From “borrower” in the Middle Ages, the West became “lender” in modern times, lending to Islam what the latter had long forgotten as its own home-grown product <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>Thus not only have the East and West “met”; they have acted, reacted and interacted, in the past, as in the present <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li><li>With mutual understanding and goodwill, [they] may well continue to do so far into the future with benefit to both sides <strong>(Volume 5)</strong></li></ul><p></p>"
