    "title": "First Temple (ca. 957 BCE-587 BCE)",
    "slug": "first-temple-ca-957-bce-587-bce",
    "bodyHtml": "<p>Only the High Priest could enter <strong>the Holy of Holies</strong><sup>[117]</sup><strong> </strong>(Hebrew:<em> Qōdhesh haq-Qādhāshîm</em>; Arabic: <em>Quds al-Aqdās</em>).</p><p><strong>The First Temple (</strong>(Hebrew: <em>ha-Bêth har-Ri’shôn </em>or <em>Bêth ham-Miqdāsh</em>; Arabic: <em>Haykal Sulayman, al-Haykal al-Awwal, </em>or <em>Bayt al-Maqdis al-Awwal</em>)) or Solomon’s Temple was built by the Prophet Solomon (d. ca. 910 BCE) remained standing for about three hundred and seventy years, which was from its completion around 957 BCE until its destruction by the Kingdom of Neo-Babylonia in 587 BCE. Solomon placed the Ark of the Covenant in the Holy of Holies of the First Temple, which the inner sanctuary of the Temple at its further extremity and had no windows. The <strong>Sadducees</strong><sup>[118]</sup><strong> </strong>made up one of the most important lines of High Priests in the First and Second Temples. They referred to themselves—as “<em>Benē Ṣādôq</em>” (Arabic: <em>Banū Ṣādūq</em> or <em>Ṣadūq</em>, which is the preferred rendition of the name;<em> </em>the Sons or Children of <em>Ṣādôq</em> or Zadok),<sup>[119]</sup> from which we get the word “Sadducee” (Hebrew: <em>Ṣādôqī</em>; Arabic: <em>Ṣādūqī</em>), which can also be rendered more broadly as “Zadokite<em>.</em>”<em> Benē Ṣādôq</em>—the Sons of Zadok—constituted the great Priestly line of Zadok. They were the descendants by direct lineage of the High Priest Ṣādôq (Zadok), who is frequently mentioned in the Old Testament and presided in Jerusalem during the days of the Prophet-King David (See, 2 Samuel, 8:17) and then into the times of his son the Prophet-King Solomon, who built the First Temple, where Ṣādôq was the first High Priest to fill the office of the High Priest. The Prophet Ezekiel—who himself was an Aaronite of the Line of Zadok—designated his paternal cousins <em>Benē Ṣādôq</em> as the only legitimate hereditary Priests of the restored Second Temple (Ezekiel, 40:46; 43:19; 44:15; 48:11). <strong>The Prophet Jeremiah</strong><sup>[120]</sup> warned the Children of Israel that <strong>King Nebuchadnezzar II</strong><sup>[121]</sup> of Babylon was a cruel and powerful ruler but would soon prove to be the instrument of God’s Anger against the Children of Israel. In 597 BCE, the Prophet’s ominous forewarnings began to come true. Nebuchadnezzar besieged Jerusalem from that year until 589 BCE, The city fell in 587 BCE, and in 586 BCE, Nebuchadnezzar II completely destroyed Jerusalem and the First Temple. Today, not a single stone remains of the First or Second Temple.</p><ul><li>The Design of the First Temple <strong>(Volume 14) </strong><ul><li>The Temple was long and open on one of its shorter sides. The interior was divided into three parts: a vestibule (Ulam; from the root “to be in front of”), a worship room (Hekal, meaning “palace” and “temple” in Hebrew and Phoenician, which was later called the “Holy Place,” and lastly the Debir (back room), which was later called the “Holy of Holies,” which was reserved for the Ark of the Covenant. The Temple was 20 cubits wide, the Ulam was 10 cubits long, the Hekal was 40 cubits, and the Debir was 20 cubits. The Hekal and Debir were treated a a single whole (1 Kings, 6:2). Together, they formed “the House,” that is, the Temple. Together, they were 60 cubits long. See 1 Kings, 6:16-17.</li></ul></li><li>Solomon's Building of the Temple <strong>Volume 14</strong><ul><li>The Hebrew Bible identifies him as the builder of the First Temple in Jerusalem, [4] beginning in the fourth year of his reign, using the vast wealth he and his father had accumulated. He dedicated the temple to Yahweh , the God of Israel. [7] He is portrayed as great in wisdom , wealth and power beyond either of the previous kings of the country, but also as a king who sinned. His sins included idolatry , marrying foreign women and, ultimately, turning away from Yahweh, and they led to the kingdom's being torn in two during the reign of his son Rehoboam. </li></ul></li><li>The Meaning of the First Temple and the Gravity of Its Destruction<ul><li>While the First Temple stood, it was the outward symbol of God’s presence among the Children of Israel and of their reciprocal devotion to Him. Its destruction became that of His seeming withdrawal and of their own defection from Him. The Book of Hymns of the Dead Sea Scrolls says: “But for them that transgress against Your word/ You will ordain dispersal/ among all the peoples on earth, passing sentence on them/ that they be cut off.”</li></ul></li></ul>"
