    "title": "Rabbinic Tradition, Its Emergence, & Growth",
    "slug": "rabbinic-tradition-its-emergence-growth",
    "bodyHtml": "<p><strong>The</strong> <strong>Jabneh Era</strong><sup>[150]</sup></p><p><strong>The Rabbinic Tradition</strong>, Rabbinic Judaism is Post-Christian.<strong> The Rabbinical Tradition, Rabbinic Judaism, or Talmudic Judaism: </strong>The <strong>Mishnah,</strong><sup>[151]</sup> <strong>Gemara</strong>,<sup>[152]</sup> and <strong>the Talmud</strong>.<sup>[153]</sup> Rabbinic Judaism grew up—in fact—in direct reaction against early Christianity—especially against the Community of Hebrew or Judaic Christians, who were literally <strong>“Jewish Christians”</strong> and unequivocally challenged Rabbinical authority.<sup>[154]</sup></p><p><strong>Mishnah,</strong><sup>[155]</sup> <strong>Gemara</strong>,<sup>[156]</sup> and <strong>the Talmud</strong>.<sup>[157]</sup></p><p>“<strong>the Jews</strong>.” <sup>[158]</sup><strong>               </strong></p>"
