    "index": 175,
    "title": "Muḥammadan Reality (al-Ḥaqīqa al-Muḥammadiyya) & the Perfect Man (al-Insān al-Kāmil)",
    "slug": "muhammadan-reality-al-haqiqa-al-muhammadiyya-the-perfect-man-al-insan-al-kamil",
    "bodyHtml": "<p><strong><em>Henological Ascent &amp; Descent in Terms of the Muḥammadan Reality &amp; Perfect Man</em></strong></p><ul><li>Looking at the above Platonist perspective from the Akbarian point of view, the Akbarian view focuses upon the Muḥammadan Reality and the Insān al-Kāmil: “He was at a proximity of two bow-lengths or even nearer” (The Star, 53:9). <strong>(Volume 7b) </strong></li><li>The Shaykh al-Akbar identifies the Muḥammadan Reality (al-Ḥaqīqa al-Muḥammadiyya) as the Archetypal point of both the origin of the descent and the point of return of the asent. Dawūd al-Qayṣarī refers to the origin in his commentary on the Fuṣūṣ. He says: <ul><li>The first thing to attain individuality (fardiyya) was indeed his immutable archetype, because the first thing that emanated by the holiest emanation from the archetypes was his immutable archetype. Likewise the first thing from the cosmos which was existentiated by the holy emanation in extramental particulars was his sanctified spirit. As he said, “The first thing God created was my light.”  (<strong>Volume 7b)</strong></li></ul></li><li>This Archetypical Light manifests itself in place and time in the historical personage of the Prophet Muḥammad, where it is referred to not as the Muḥammadan Reality but as the Perfect Man (al-Insān al-Kāmil). The Perfect Man has “descended” through all the degrees of ontological reality. In history, the Perfect Man “unifies” the multiple planes of being, of which the corporeal world is only an image and an instantiation.<strong>Volume 7b</strong></li><li>The Perfect Man is the fifth of the Divine Presences (al-Ḥaḍrāt), embodying in himself the four prior Presences:<ul><li>The Permanent Archetypes (al-Aʿyān al-Thābita), of which the Muḥammadan Reality is the first.</li><li>The Spirits.</li><li>The Imagination.</li><li>Material Existence.</li></ul></li><li>The natural world subsists as things-known in God’s eternal Knowledge. In their Archetypical Being, they are branches of the first Determination, namely the Immutable Archetype of the Muḥammadan Reality. When these archetypes “smell the fragrance of Being,” in the sense of being made concrete, that is, when ontological posteriority is manifested as through the weeping of the palm trunk in the Prophet’s Mosque, the salutations of the stones to him in Mecca, and the love of Mount Uḥud for him and the believers. Just as the Immutable Archetypes are particularizations of al-Ḥaqīqa al-Muḥammadiyya, so too is the natural world made up of manifold particularizations of the Perfect Man (al-Insān al-Kāmil). <strong>Volume 7b</strong></li><li>The pure being of “Absolute Being” means that it is an “existence” unconditioned by being determined by qualifications (muṭlaq al-qayd). WHAT IS BEYOND BEING This is precisely what “beyond being” denotes in the Platonic tradition. Thus, the Akbarian tradition speaks of the Absolute in Itself, rather than in terms of a unity that excludes all determination. God is muta‘ayyin in Himself. For He is Himself, and He is not the world. But this ta‘ayyun does not represent anything analogous to the individuation of any finite being, since all of our examples of individuation involve the individuation of an essence or property that is distinct from the individuated thing itself, whereas there is nothing that is prior to or with God. This is God as al-Aḥadiyya (exclusive Unity), the absolute principle of unity, which according to al-Qayṣarī, is the essence of “existence” (ḥaqīqat al-wujūd) in itself. The “first determination” (al-ta‘ayyun al-awwal) is al-waḥda (determinate unity), the unified principle of the emergence of multiplicity upon which the unfolding of creation depends. <em>It is evidently also acounted for in terms of unity, as the first finite determination of the infinite Divine plenitude such that we might capture its meta-principial intellgible unity in the term “infity-limit” and indeed, it is the most perfect determination possible, namely of al-ḥaqīqa al-Muḥammadiyya (the Muḥammadan Reality</em>). The second determination is al-Wāḥidiyya (unified multiplicity) and represents the actual distinct emergence of the specific principles of all subsequent multiplicity, namely, the Immutable Archetypes as images of the Divine Names. in the Akbarian tradition, even created reality is defined in terms of henological participation. Mulla Fenari &amp; the Single Principle of Unity: Mulla Fenari states: “The world” is the very fact of all multiplicitous phenomena being rendered intelligible within a single principle of unity.  <strong>Volume 9 </strong></li><li>The golden sequence begins with mathematical zero (0), which represents nothingness and the negation of all quantity and multiplicity. Metaphysically, zero--especially in the golden series--represents the first level of being: the “presence of God’s exclusive oneness” (ḥaḍrat aḥadiyya), which excludes all quantity, multiplicity, and creation. At this first level of being, God reveals Himself as “the One and Absolute” (al-Aḥad), and the uncreated cosmos lies dormant in nothingness. Next comes the initial number one (1) and with it, the second level of existence, which brings creation to the threshold of being. This is called the “presence of God’s inclusive oneness” (ḥaḍrat wāḥidiyya), in which God manifests Himself as “the One” (al-Wāḥid), which is where creation and multiplicity begin. Then the number one (1) is repeated a second time, which represents the third level of existence--the first creative act--which brings forth the most perfect of all entities, implicitly including in it all that will unfold in the infinite potentialities of all-possibility unto eternity. In Islamic metaphysics, this first perfect and comprehensive creation is called “the Muḥammadan light” (al-nūr al-Muḥammadī) or “the Muḥammadan reality” (al-ḥaqīqa al-Muḥammadiyya). <strong>Volume 9 </strong></li></ul>"
